segments.text: No, I'm not sorry that I served in Vietnam.
I'm proud that I served in Vietnam.
I don't have any regrets about my personal service in Vietnam.
Just looking back at 15 or 20 years ago, I wish that it could have been handled maybe differently than it was at the time.
Do you think we did anything right in Vietnam?
I started to say that we may have very, very good withdraw from Vietnam, but I'm not sure I think that was almost kind of botched.
I don't know.
I'm not sure I can answer that we we did anything that was of any value in Vietnam.
We set out to
preserve the government of South Vietnam, that we didn't do that.
If we set out to show the world that the United States is a military power to be reckoned with, we didn't do that.
I think we tarnished our military image.
I think we tarnished our worldwide image by making the decision to be there and not accomplishing whatever purposes we thought we were there for.
We probably really didn't do anything right in Vietnam.
What was it like coming home?
Well, it was a very joyful experience.
As I recall, only a few days before I left Vietnam, a regular dinner that we had in our unit for people, newcomers and people that were leaving.
I got to make a farewell address, and I told the gathering that I was leaving Vietnam with mixed emotions, joy and happiness.
So that's kind of the way I felt about coming home.
I was glad to be home.
I know when we landed at Travis Air Force Base, the entire plane broke into cheers and applause.
So I was glad to be home.
I had missed my family.
I was glad to be back to see them.
What was the biggest adjustment?
Probably changing my language from military language back to acceptable civilian language.
And I guess adjusting to a wife and a daughter, back living with them.
That's probably about the only thing I can think of.
It's kind of very different living with the guys than with the family.
Well, I really, it is, and I, you know, I lived alone.
I had my own room.

It was just a room, but just to change a little bit on a lifestyle that was a little restrained and that I didn't have a lot of freedom of movement, but not living with somebody daily, not really having a...
responsibility for a wife and a child.
Even though I did have their responsibility, I didn't have daily contact with them to have their responsibility.
How often did you, did you receive mail or could you call or what contact did you have with home?
I had, I probably have a couple of bushel baskets full of letters around here somewhere that Linda wrote me almost daily and
And I wrote her almost daily.
We sent tapes back and forth to each other.
I got to talk to her on the telephone probably five or six times through the, I don't know what they called it, but it was a radio connect up where I could

get on the radio kind of ham operators type thing and we could connect up with a ham operator at Fort Bliss in El Paso and then he would call Linda on the phone and I could talk to her that way and then I think on three occasions twice I went into into Saigon into the

it was the USO club in Saigon and they had a telephone that I could call long distance and talk to her just like a long distance telephone call and I did that twice I think and then on Christmas Eve I got to call her from the base just on a regular long distance hookup so I talked to her occasionally and we wrote a lot
And she sent me lots of care packages.
When you came home, how were you welcomed by people outside your family?
Oh, I think I was well received by the people outside of my family, as well as in my family.
Most of the folks in this part of the world were not war protesters.
They were not out burning their draft cards or the United States, their American flag.
So, you know, I think they looked on me as somebody who served my country and did my job and didn't think that I was a murderer or a scoundrel or whatever.
Looking back, what was the worst part of the war for you?
The separation from my family.
I think that was it.
What about the best?
I've got some pretty good friends that I made when I was in Vietnam.
I don't see a lot now, but we were very close.
So I think I made some awfully good friends.
You can't beat coming home.
It's been the best thing.
I made some very good friends when I was over there.
Do you think the friendships in war are much closer than at a war?
I mean, besides family bonds.
I think that's probably true of people that served in World War II and in World War I more so than it is of people that served in Vietnam.
understanding that I do not serve in a combat situation and I suspect that bonds between people that serve in combat become a lot closer than people that serve in a rear area.
If there was such a thing as a rear area in Vietnam.
I would say that they do have strong bonds
But it's almost going to be, in my opinion, tied to the level of danger or risk that they're exposed to is to how close those bonds are.
Or how estranged, if that's the proper word, they would be.
I would think that you could have love-hate relationships depending on the interaction between the people in a stress situation.
Mm-hmm.
Kind of sometimes you're too close to... That's right.
Too close to people.
You said that you officed with someone from Civil Affairs.
That's right.
What did you learn about the Civil Affairs operations?
Mainly the Civil Affairs was an operation that I saw.
It was an operation to educate,
the Vietnamese to communicate and interact with the Vietnamese to basically try to help them adjust to and adapt to the presence of the United States military in Vietnam.
It was an effort to win them over to the side of the United States
by education and involvement, communication, participation in their daily lives, aid in medical, farming, that type of aid.
So it was an education and an assistance program.
How effective do you think it was?
It'd be purely a guess on my part.
I never really saw it on the level out in the field where they were dealing with those folks.
I think it had some good effects, but it's probably like any, like I would probably feel if the Germans or the Russians or anyone were to invade the United States and then start trying to
give me propaganda to tell me how I ought to like to have them over here.
So I think it probably was effective for some, but not effective for everyone.
But it's a process I think you have to do.
Did you ever have to deal with any incidents between Vietnamese and Americans?
In cases?
No.
Well, no.
I did not handle any files where we had any Vietnamese nationals involved.
I can recall that now.
I wasn't involved in anything similar to the Cali incident or the Mila incident or anything like that.
Those types of things were handled at the general court martial level.
And there were some handled in the long bin, which is right where I was.
But that was all at the general quarters level.
Well, there were some handled at the two field force level, too.
But I didn't handle any of them.
I had no direct involvement with them.
Do you think, because you have such a short tour duty, did that affect any of the legal operations?
I mean, did they just bring one lighter in and one out?
Yeah, I don't think it did.
Most of the people that came into Vietnam in the legal area were already experienced from a stateside assignment or assignment in Europe.
So they, it was a very easy transition.
Did you see it, I guess, harming any other positions?
I didn't, not that I can say that I saw it harming any other positions.
I don't really think that they had any problem making those transitions.
Somebody answer the phone.
That'll look great on your tape.
No, I don't think they had any problems just because of the short tourism duty.
But you had the same commander, though, Colonel?
Yes.
He got there just about a few months before I did, and we were on the same plane going home.
He let the same guy in.
Do you ever see him?
No, I haven't seen him since we got off the plane at Travis Air Force Base.
Okay.
Summing up, is there anything else you want to add?
No, I don't know.
I can't think of anything.
I can't think of anything.
